        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In this Science Goal we aim to measure the continuum, detect and image weak and broad emission of the CO 3-2 line in the stellar-merger remnants of V4332 Sgr.

Because one of the aims of this SG is to detect a spectral line, we choose 'spectral line' mode in the OT (but the proposed setup is equivalent to the 'single continuum' mode). The choice of band 7 is explained in the science justification -- it is dictated by the desire to observe the CO(3-2) transition and reach a resolution of ~0.1 arcsec. The central frequency was chosen to cover the CO(3-2) line in one of the subbands. The lowest possible spectral resolution which was emplyed in our setup of 26-27 km/s is fully satisfactory for our spectral observations of the molecular line (as the expected FWHM is of about 130 km/s). It also provides a broad coverage of the continuum which allows a very good measurement of the continuum fluxes, what is another aim of this proposal. 

As explained in the scientific justification, the molecular emission may be extended up to a region of 0.6 arcsec in diameter. We would like to resolve the emission, if present, and therefore request the extended configuration of the main ALMA array. In bands 7 this results in the resolution of ~0.1 arcsec which is perfectly siutable for this project. As 0.6 arcsec constitutes rather an upper limit on the expected size of the emission region, there is no need for the Compact Array. 

The continuum flux of V4332 Sgr near 346 GHz is easy to predict from the SED of the object (see Fig. 2 in the scientific justification). A linear extrapolation of the available data to 346 GHz gives a flux density of F=3 mJy. We wish to reach S/N in continuum of about 45 or a sensitivity of 1 mJy per 0.12" beam. This rms level guarantees good S/N even if the spectral index steepens with wavelength due to opacity effects (what was not taken into account in our linear extrapolation). It is unlikely that the continuum source will be resolved, but at the requested S/N we will obtain satisfactory results even if the source turns out to be slightly extended. The requested rms can be reached in 45 min of total observing time or 12 min on source (giving 27% observing efficiency). We note that requesting lower rms values would result in very ineffective observations.  

We have no constraints on the molecular emission in V4332 Sgr except the APEX upper limits with the rms noise level of 200 mJy per 24 km/s bin (see the scientific justification). With the requested sensitivity of 1 mJy at a similar spectral resolution (26 km/s), we will acquire spectra 200 times deeper than those at APEX, what is fully satisfactory. This is also satisfactory if the source of molecular emission is extended. Since the line flux is the quantity we would like to derive in these observations, we are not able to specify the resulting S/N ratios for the spectral observations.   </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
