        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In this Science Goal we aim to measure the continuum and detect weak and broad emission of the CO 3-2 line in the stellar-merger remnants of V1309 Sco.

Because one of the aims of this SG is to detect a spectral line, we choose the 'spectral line' mode in the OT (but the proposed setup is equivalent to the 'single continuum' mode). The choice of band 7 is explained in the science justification - it is dictated by the desire to observe the CO(3-2) transition, which strongest among those avaible. The frequency was intentionally chosen to cover the CO(3-2) line in the LSB. The lowest possible spectral resolution of this setup of 26-27 km/s is fully satisfactory for our spectral observations of the molecular line (as the expected FWHM is of about 150 km/s). It also provides a broad coverage of the continuum which allows a very good measurement of the continuum fluxes, what is another aim of this proposal. 

We optimize the setup for V1309 Sco to maximize the sensitivity and are do not attempt to resolve the source. As we expect V1309 Sco to be a point source, there is no need for the Compact Array. 

The continuum flux of V1309 Sco near 346 GHz is easy to predict from the SED of the object (see Fig. 2 in the scientific justification). A linear extrapolation of the available data to 346 GHz gives a flux density of F=6 mJy. We wish to reach S/N in continuum above 50 (or sensitivity better than 2 mJy). Such sensitivity result however in very inefficient observations of 10% (3 min on source out of 30 min of total observing time). Therefore, we request sensitivity of 1 mJy which results in continuum S/N of 95 and observation-time efficiency of about 30%. This rms level guarantees good S/N even if the spectral index steepens with wavelength due to opacity effects (what was not taken into account in our linear extrapolation). The requested rms can be reached in 42 min of total observing time or 12 min on source.

We have no constraints on the fluxes of molecular emission in V1309 Sco except the APEX upper limits with rms noise level of 200 mJy per 24 km/s (see the scientific justification). With the requested sensitivity of 1 mJy at a similar spectral resolution, we will acquire spectra 200 times deeper than those at APEX, what is fully satisfactory. Since the line flux is the quantity we would like to derive in these observations, we are not able to specify the resulting S/N ratios for the spectral observations.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
