    <prp:abstract>We propose to observe emission of circumstellar dust and gas around two eruptive objects, V1309 Sco &amp; V4332 Sgr, which belong to a group of transients known as red novae. It has been shown that these objects recently (in 1994 and 2008), i.e. 'before our eyes', experienced a stellar merger. We propose ALMA observations of the continuum and in the CO(3-2) line in both objects. Our main aims are (1) to constrain masses and physical sizes of dusty disks which were formed in those objects just after the merger, and (2) to trace the molecular material which was dispersed during the eruption or which is stored in the coolest parts of the disks. This will shed more light on the phenomena that take place during and just after a stellar merger in binary systems. It will also provide observational base for a quantitative analysis of what is the total energy and angular-momentum balance in those complex systems. </prp:abstract>
